hands_on_practices.solution:
1. Buchdahl limit:
$$M_{\max}=\frac{4c^4}{9\sqrt{6\pi G^3\epsilon_0}}\,. $$

2. Energy density at transition:
$$\epsilon_0=\frac{g}{8\pi^2(\hbar c)^3}\,\mu^4,\quad g=2,\ \mu=m_\chi c^2.$$
Thus
$$\epsilon_0=\frac{2}{8\pi^2(\hbar c)^3}(m_\chi c^2)^4
=\frac{m_\chi^4c^5}{4\pi^2\hbar^3}\,. $$

3. Substitution into Buchdahl expression:
$$M_{\max}
=\frac{4c^4}{9\sqrt{6\pi G^3\;\frac{m_\chi^4c^5}{4\pi^2\hbar^3}}}
=\frac{4c^4}{9\sqrt{\frac{3}{2\pi}\,G^3m_\chi^4c^5/\hbar^3}}
=\frac{4}{9}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{3}}
\frac{c^4\hbar^{3/2}}{G^{3/2}m_\chi^2c^{5/2}}. $$

4. Simplify powers of $c$ and group constants:
$$M_{\max}
=\frac{4}{9}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{3}}
\frac{(\hbar c)^{3/2}}{G^{3/2}m_\chi^2}
=\frac{4}{9}\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{3}}
\frac{(\hbar c/G)^{3/2}}{m_\chi^2}\,. $$
